   <text>
      <body>
         <div>
            <pb facs="#facs_1" n="1" xml:id="img_0001"/>
            <pb facs="#facs_2" n="2" xml:id="img_0002"/>
            <ab facs="#facs_2_tr_1">
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_3" n="N001"/>Antioch - April 1960
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_4" n="N002"/><hi style="text-decoration: underline;">Religion and Culture: Fundamental Concepts</hi>
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_6" n="N003"/>1. The general subject of {all} the two lectures and the
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_7" n="N004"/>discussion is <Religion>religion</Religion> and <Culture>culture</Culture>. These two words belong
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_9" n="N005"/>to the many who have fallen into the abyss of last words
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_11" n="N006"/>which must be saved before we can use them for anyone's
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_13" n="N007"/>salvation. - This is always necessary: <rs type="person" key=", tillich_person_id__1806">Socrates</rs>, <rs type="person" key=", tillich_person_id__80">Aristotle</rs>, the
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_15" n="N008"/>scholastics, the encyclopedist, the epistemologist of the
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_17" n="N009"/>Kantian school, the semanticists of today. - But always
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_18" n="N010"/>the danger to stick to words, forgetting that {words} in
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_19" n="N011"/>genuine words the power of the subject matter is present.
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_20" n="N012"/>(Hebrew: "dibar" = word <hi style="text-decoration: underline;">and</hi> matter grasped in it. Greek: logos =
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_21" n="N013"/>word and rational structure of reality). Therefore dealing with
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_22" n="N014"/>words is never dealing with words alone, but with encounters
               <lb facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_23" n="N015"/>with reality: The justification of philo - logie, "love of words."
